{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}} {{Infobox Airliner accident|name=Sabena Junkers Ju 52 Ostend crash | Date=16 November 1937 | coordinates = {{coord|51|12|3.42|N|2|53|31.42|E|type:airport_region:BE|display=it}}| Type=[[Controlled flight into terrain]]<!--A building is counted as terrain--> in poor weather | occurrence_type = Accident | image=JU 52 3M.jpg | caption= A JU 52 similar to the accident aircraft | Site=Ostend, Belgium | Fatalities=12{{efn|The Princess of Hesse was heavily pregnant when she boarded the aircraft and the body of a baby was found in the wreckage, believed to have been born during the flight.<ref name="times2" />}} | Injuries=0 | Aircraft Type=[[Junkers Ju 52|Junkers Ju 52/3m]] | Operator=Sabena | Tail Number=OO-AUB | Passengers=8 | Crew=4 | Survivors = 0 | }}
On 16 November 1937 a [[Junkers Ju 52|Junkers Ju 52/3m]] owned by Belgian airline [[SABENA]], operating as a scheduled international [[Airline|passenger flight]] from Cologne, Germany,{{clarify|reason=Planecrashinfo.com states that the aircraft departed from Cologne; the Western Argus - in another article on the same page as the source used - states that Munich was the departure point|date=May 2018}} to London, England, crashed near [[Ostend]], Belgium. The aircraft hit a tall factory chimney while attempting to land at Steene aerodrome near Ostend, Belgium. The accident killed prominent members of the Hesse royal family on the way to London for the wedding of [[Louis, Prince of Hesse and by Rhine]].
==Accident== The flight from Frankfurt to London was scheduled to stop at Ostend Airport but diverted to Steene Aerodrome due to the bad weather. The aircraft hit the chimney of a brick factory and crashed, bursting into flames.<ref name="times1">{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=A Tragic Air Crash - Eleven Dead |day_of_week=Wedensday |date=17 November 1937 |page_number=16 |issue=47844 |column= }}</ref>
All eleven passengers and crew who boarded the aircraft died. The remains of Grand Duchess Cecilie's newborn child were found among the wreckage; a Belgian official enquiry into the crash indicated that the birth was the reason the pilot was attempting to land despite the poor weather conditions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Birth of Royal Infant seen as Cause of Crash|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=950&dat=19371123&id=0MwLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=NlUDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4248,1220727|accessdate=28 June 2012|newspaper=the Evening Independent|date=23 November 1937}}</ref><ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,758458,00.html Curse of Hesse – [[Time Magazine]]]</ref>
==Crew and passengers== The aircraft had a crew of four: pilot, wireless operator and mechanic as well as a German engineer.<ref name="times1" />
The members of royalty among the passengers were:<ref name="times1" /> *[[Georg Donatus, Hereditary Grand Duke of Hesse|Hereditary Grand Duke Georg Donatus of Hesse]] (The Prince of Hesse) *[[Princess Cecilie of Greece and Denmark|Princess Cecilie, the Grand Duchess of Hesse]] *[[Princess Eleonore of Solms-Hohensolms-Lich|The Dowager Grand Duchess of Hesse]] *[[Prince Ludwig of Hesse and by Rhine|Prince Ludwig]]{{efn|also known as Prince Louis}} *[[Prince Alexander of Hesse and by Rhine (1933-1937)|Prince Alexander]] *Georg Donatus' and Cecilie's newborn infant
==Aircraft== The aircraft was a three-engined [[Junkers Ju 52|Junkers Ju 52/3m]] airliner operated by [[SABENA]] and [[aircraft registration|registered]] in Belgium as ''OO-AUB''.
==Aftermath== The wedding of [[Prince Louis of Hesse and by Rhine|Louis]] with Margaret Campbell-Geddes, daughter of Sir [[Auckland Geddes, 1st Baron Geddes|Auckland Geddes]] was brought forward to the morning after the accident.<ref name="times1" /> Baron Riedesel would have been Louis' best man; their friend Oliver Chesterton stood in as best man; the ceremony was small and solemn with the guests in mourning clothes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article34960912 |title=A Twelfth Victim. |newspaper=[[Western Argus|Western Argus (Kalgoorlie, WA : 1916 – 1938)]] |location=Kalgoorlie, WA |date=23 November 1937 |accessdate=28 June 2012 |page=19 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref name="times1" />
Immediately following the wedding, Prince Louis and his wife Margaret travelled to Belgium and visited a hospital where the victims' bodies had been laid out.<ref name="times2">{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Ostend Air Disaster |day_of_week=Thursday |date=18 November 1937 |page_number=14 |issue=47845 |column= }}</ref>
The Hereditary Grand Duke and Duchess' fourteen-month-old daughter, [[Princess Johanna of Hesse and by Rhine|Johanna]], was the only one of the family who was not on board the aircraft. She was adopted by her uncle Louis in early 1938. Johanna died of [[meningitis]] in 1939.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}
With the death of the childless Prince Louis in 1968, the male line of the Hesse and by Rhine became extinct.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}
