The '''Institute for Energy and Environmental Research''' (IEER) focuses on the environmental safety of [[nuclear weapons]] production, [[ozone layer depletion]], and other issues relating to [[energy]].<ref name = erin/> IEER publishes a variety of books on energy-related issues,<ref>[[Arjun Makhijani]] (2007). [https://books.google.com/books?id=y_PQg-NvBX0C&dq=%22Institute+for+Energy+and+Environmental+Research%22&source=gbs_navlinks_s Carbon-free and nuclear-free: a roadmap for U.S. energy policy] RDR Books.</ref><ref>Brice Smith (2006). [https://books.google.com/books?id=5HdddXH_1ngC&dq=Institute+for+Energy+and+Environmental+Research&source=gbs_navlinks_s Insurmountable risks: the dangers of using nuclear power to combat global climate change] RDR Books.</ref> conducts workshops for activists on nuclear issues, and sponsors international symposia and educational outreach projects. IEER was established in 1987 and is based in [[Takoma Park, Maryland]].<ref name = erin>Erin E. Dooley. [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1240717/pdf/ehp0110-a0016e.pdf Institute for Energy and Environmental Research] ''Environmental Health Perspectives'', Vol. 110 , No. 1, January 2002, p. A 19.</ref>
[[Arjun Makhijani]] is President of the Institute for Energy and Environmental Research.
